The Voice is an American singing competition television series broadcast on NBC. It premiered during the spring television cycle on April 26, 2011, and expanded into the fall cycle with the premiere of the third season on September 10, 2012. Based on the original The Voice of Holland, and part of The Voice franchise it has aired seventeen seasons and aims to find currently unsigned singing talent (solo or duets, professional and amateur) contested by aspiring singers, age 13 or over, drawn from public auditions.
The winner is determined by television viewers voting by telephone, Internet, SMS text, and iTunes Store purchases of the audio-recorded artists' vocal performances. They receive US$100,000 and a record deal with Universal Music Group for winning the competition. The winners of the sixteen seasons have been Javier Colon, Jermaine Paul, Cassadee Pope, Danielle Bradbery, Tessanne Chin, Josh Kaufman, Craig Wayne Boyd, Sawyer Fredericks, Jordan Smith, Alisan Porter, Sundance Head, Chris Blue, Chloe Kohanski, Brynn Cartelli, Chevel Shepherd, Maelyn Jarmon, and Todd Tilghman, respectively.

The end of the frontier was a phrase used by Frederick Jackson Turner in his 1893 essay The Significance of the Frontier in American History to describe the claim that the availability of free land in the 19th century was a major factor in the transformation of American democracy and society. In his essay, Turner argued that the American frontier established a process of development that gave American democracy its character and identity. The idea of the frontier was important to American national identity, and the frontier thesis was promoted by generations of scholars to explain the characteristics of the American people and their institutions.
The frontier thesis was one of the earliest scholarly interpretations and remains one of the most influential ones. Turner's ideas persist in scholarship, and recent historians have combined the thesis with other interpretations, such as the importance of slavery to the American economy, the role of class in American politics, and the importance of the existence of a state in the development of American industry.
Turner's frontier thesis was a significant development in the historiography of the United States. The Girl Scouts of the USA (GSUSA) is a youth organization for girls in the United States and American girls living abroad. The organization was founded by Juliette Gordon Low in 1912 and was originally intended as an organization for working-class girls, as most other youth groups focused on middle- and upper-class girls.
The Girl Scouts is one of the largest organizations for girls in the United States, with over 2.5 million youth members and over 800,000 adult members. The organization has a strong presence in many communities throughout the country, with over 50 million alumnae.
The Girl Scouts of the USA is a nonprofit organization that is funded through membership dues, donations, and corporate sponsorships. The organization also receives funding from the federal government through the Girl Scouts of the USA Foundation.
The Girl Scouts of the USA is a member of the World Association of Girl Guides and Girl Scouts, an international organization that unites over 10 million girls and women in 145 countries.

Black Panther is an American superhero film based on the Marvel Comics character of the same name. Produced by Marvel Studios and distributed by Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures, it is the eighteenth film in the Marvel Cinematic Universe (MCU). The film is directed by Ryan Coogler, who co-wrote the screenplay with Joe Robert Cole, and stars Chadwick Boseman as T'Challa / Black Panther, alongside Michael B. Jordan, Lupita Nyong'o, Danai Gurira, Martin Freeman, Daniel Kaluuya, Letitia Wright, Winston Duke, Angela Bassett, Forest Whitaker, and Andy Serkis. In Black Panther, the Wakandans face a threat from the intergovernmental organization known as the International Security, Coordination, and Intelligence Agency (S.I.C.I.A.).

The show was a hit with audiences and critics alike, and it won numerous awards, including five Emmy Awards and two Golden Globe Awards. It was also one of the most successful sitcoms of all time, and it is still considered one of the best sitcoms ever made.

The U.S. withdrew from Vietnam in 1973 after signing the Paris Peace Accords, a peace agreement between the United States and North Vietnam that promised a cease-fire and withdrawal of U.S. troops.
The agreement was signed in Paris on January 27, 1973, and was officially implemented on January 28, 1973. The U.S. military began withdrawing troops from Vietnam in accordance with the agreement, and the last U.S. troops left Vietnam on March 29, 1973.
However, the peace agreement did not last long, and fighting between North Vietnam and South Vietnam resumed in 1975. North Vietnam eventually captured Saigon, the capital of South Vietnam, on April 30, 1975, and the war ended with the unification of Vietnam under Communist rule.

The American Revolution began with the Boston Tea Party in 1773. The Boston Tea Party was an act of rebellion against the British government. The Boston Tea Party was a protest against the British government’s attempt to tax the American colonies without their consent.
The American Revolution ended with the Treaty of Paris in 1783. The Treaty of Paris was a peace treaty between the United States and Great Britain. The Treaty of Paris recognized the independence of the United States.

A 47-year-old man from Britain has become the first person to break the 4-minute mile barrier without the aid of special shoes or oxygen.
Alan Webb ran the mile in 3 minutes, 43.40 seconds on Saturday at the Prefontaine Classic in Eugene, Oregon.
The former high school and college star had run the mile in 3 minutes, 46.91 seconds in 2001, but that was done in a race that was slowed by a heavy rainstorm.
He had tried to break the barrier before, but failed.
The record of 3 minutes, 43.13 seconds was set by Hicham El Guerrouj of Morocco in 1999.
The 4-minute mile was thought to be an unbreakable barrier until Roger Bannister did it in 1954.
He died on March 3 at the age of 83.
